{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500102"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1609"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1609"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.3,0.33,0.12,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56766"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"863"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37001"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56766"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman is referred to the gastroenterology clinic with a six week history of vomiting, weight loss and diarrhoea. Her medical history includes mild asthma and insomnia. Ten years ago she had a distal gastrectomy for a perforated peptic ulcer. Her medications include 1-2 puffs salbutamol PRN and 10mg melatonin in the evenings. She is an ex-smoker with a five pack-year history and drinks 1-2 glasses of red wine each night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious and thin, with a measured weight of 57 kg (previously 65 kg according to the GP referral letter). The rest of the examination is unremarkable, aside from some mild epigastric tenderness. As part of the investigative work-up requested by the gastroenterologist, the patient undergoes an upper gastrointestinal endoscopy (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Taking the image into account, which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Achalasia","Corkscrew oesophagus","Eosinophilic oesophagitis","Coeliac disease","Gastro-colic fistula"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Egastro-colic fistula\u003C/strong\u003E. The endoscopic view shows the characteristic triangular haustral folds of the transverse colon. The only way the endoscope could have got into this structure would be by way of a gastro-colic fistula. A gastro-colic fistula, is in the majority of cases, a pathologic communication between the stomach and transverse colon. The most common causes of fistula development are colonic adenocarcinoma, gastric carcinoma and peptic ulcer disease. In this particular case the fistula had formed after complicated surgery for a perforated peptic ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E cannot be reliably diagnosed via endoscopy, with oesophageal manometry the gold-standard investigation. As such, this answer option is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorkscrew oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in association with diffuse oesophageal spasm. The main symptoms include dysphagia and heart burn. Endoscopy will sometimes demonstrate a \u0022twisting\u0022 of the oesophagus, with oesophageal manometry (the gold-standard investigation) occasionally revealing the classical corkscrew appearance, however more often simply showing non-peristaltic oesophageal contractions. Corkscrew oesophagus will not influence the ability to visualise the large bowel on upper GI endoscopy, making this answer option incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E will typically present with symptoms such as difficulty swallowing, food impaction and heartburn. On endoscopy, the oesophagus will classically demonstrate longitudinal furrows, circular rings and white exudates. These changes with the appearance of circular rings are often referred to as trachealisation of the oesophagus. None of these features are present here and the triangular pattern is typical of haustral folds in the colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E will present with abdominal pain, diarrhoea and weight loss, with symptoms triggered by ingestion of gluten-containing foods. Diagnosis is established via antibody testing and small bowel biopsy, which characteristically shows villous atrophy. Coeliac disease does not explain the appearance large bowel on the upper GI endoscopy, making this answer option incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Whilst uncommon, a gastro-colic fistula will usually point to a diagnosis of malignancy.","The transverse colon can be identified endoscopically through its characteristic triangular haustral folds."],"references":["Stamatakos M, Karaiskos I, Pateras I, Alexiou I, Stefanaki C, Kontzoglou K. Gastrocolic fistulae; From Haller till nowadays. International journal of surgery (London, England). 2012;10(3):129\u201333","Razzano A, Ali M, Modayil R. Gastrocolic Fistula: A Rare Presentation of a Common Disease. Gastroenterology (New York, NY 1943). 2018;154(1)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1609"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19467"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19467"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a02538a3-f800-4bfe-b20d-ee5cd881c843.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a02538a3-f800-4bfe-b20d-ee5cd881c843.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":400,"height":300}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-21T18:22:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T10:13:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1609"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56766"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"